snippet.textDisplay: As concerns the pricing of these cars: I've noticed that all high-end  cars go through a period when they aren't as desirable as one would think, and the price reflects this. This was true for awhile of the Rolls-Royce Silver Cloud, which are now highly sought after. The Silver Shadow went through a period when they cost less than a new Ford Taurus, and are now becoming highly sought after (especially the earlier chrome bumper models of '67-'72). In roughly 10 to 20 years, I'd expect the price of  80s-'90s Rolls and Bentleys to shoot up again. This is worth keeping in mind when people point out how quickly these cars depreciate after a couple of years (from new).

snippet.textDisplay:
The Series 3 & XJ40 Daimlers (Called the Jaguar Vanden Plas in the States) had virtually all the "luxury features" of the Bentley, the leather everywhere including the sun visors, the only exception being the headlining. They also had multiple interior lights, as well as picnic tables & lambswool overmats. Remote locking was standard on the Bentleys, but then, in Europe at least, many cars had remote locking by the late 80`s, from Renaults to Fiats.

The V12 Jaguars were quicker than the Turbo R, & they handled much better (which was the deciding factor for me, when I decided to become a "Jaguar man" instead of a Bentley one, way back in the 90`s), even the 6 cylinder ones would give it a run for its money at speed, especially as the Bentley had the aerodynamics of a brick..

Also, Doug, when you close the boot, PLEASE take the key out of the lock, as the fob & other keys on the ring damage the paint, there's a dear chap..
